So let's first combine the fractions being added and set them equal to 5.  While the denominators are the same, we can combine the numerators to form one.  $\displaystyle\frac{2x + 1}{x - 1} = 5$.   Next, we multiply all terms by the denominators to remove the denominators; be careful not to write only the denominator and forget to multiply the terms. Notice that $$\begin{aligned}

&\frac{2x+1}{x-1}\\

\end{aligned}=5&&\text{Remove entire denominators from equation.} \\

\begin{aligned}

&2x+1 = 5x-5\\

\end{aligned}

$$

Now we proceed to solve the one step equation.  First, we subtract $2x$ from each side. $$\begin{aligned}

&1 = 3x-5\\

\end{aligned}$$ Recall that order matters when subtracting terms.  This is because subtracting switched the sign of the term. So let's change the sign of the old term and move it over to the other side of the equation as well. $$\begin{aligned}

&6 = 3x\\

\end{aligned}$$ Lastly, we divide by 3 on both sides. $$\begin{aligned}

&\frac{x}{1} = 2\\

\end{aligned}$$Ancillary assumption: $$\begin{aligned}

&x \neq 1 && \text{So } \frac{x}{x-1} \text{ is defined.}\\

\end{aligned}$$

